Not quite. In Christianity, yeah, we’re in a broken world, but the point is to redeem it—God becoming flesh proves the material isn’t trash. Gnosticism goes further: your body, your dirt, your taxes? All illusions to break free from. We’re not waiting for the rapture to escape, we’re waiting for new heavens and new earth—where everything’s fixed, not ditched. Big difference.

So, isn't that kind of a tenet of Stoicism that the world is flawed?

Stoicism doesn’t quite go there. They say the world has flaws, sure, but it’s all part of a rational, divine order. You accept it, live virtuously, work with it. Not escape. Gnosticism’s more like… the world’s a bad neighborhood you gotta sneak out of. Stoics? They’re just trying to keep the porch light on.

